The area of triangle $ABC$ is
\begin{align*}
[ABC] &= [ABD] + [ACD] \\
&= \frac{1}{2} \cdot BD \cdot AD + \frac{1}{2} \cdot CD \cdot AD \\
&= \frac{1}{2} \cdot AD \cdot (BD + CD) \\
&= \frac{1}{2} \cdot AD \cdot BC \\
&= \frac{1}{2} \cdot AD \cdot (BD + CD) \\
&= \frac{1}{2} \cdot AD \cdot (DE_A - BD + DE_A - CD) \\
&= \frac{1}{2} \cdot AD \cdot (2DE_A - BC) \\
&= \frac{1}{2} \cdot AD \cdot (4E_A - BC).
\end{align*}From the formula for the area of a triangle in terms of its inradius and semiperimeter, $[ABD] = rs = \frac{1}{2} AD \cdot BD,$ so $r = \frac{BD}{2}.$  Hence, $BD = 2r.$

Similarly, $CD = 2r.$  Therefore,
\[[ABC] = \frac{1}{2} \cdot AD \cdot (4E_A - 4r) = 2AD (E_A - r).\]We know that $E_A - r = I_A = \frac{7}{37} \cdot \frac{2}{\sin \frac{1}{2} \angle BAC}$ and $AD = \frac{2[ABD]}{\sin \frac{1}{2} \angle BAC} = \frac{2 \cdot \frac{1}{2} \cdot BD \cdot AD}{\sin \frac{1}{2} \angle BAC} = \frac{2r \cdot AD}{\sin \frac{1}{2} \angle BAC},$ so
\[[ABC] = 2 \cdot \frac{2r \cdot AD}{\sin \frac{1}{2} \angle BAC} \cdot \frac{7}{37} \cdot \frac{2}{\sin \frac{1}{2} \angle BAC} = \frac{56r \cdot AD}{\sin^2 \frac{1}{2} \angle BAC}.\]But $r = \frac{BD}{2}$ and $AD = \frac{2[ABD]}{\sin \frac{1}{2} \angle BAC} = \frac{2 \cdot \frac{1}{2} \cdot BD \cdot AD}{\sin \frac{1}{2} \angle BAC} = \frac{BD \cdot AD}{\sin \frac{1}{2} \angle BAC},$ so
\[[ABC] = \frac{56 \cdot \frac{BD}{2} \cdot \frac{BD \cdot AD}{\sin \frac{1}{2} \angle BAC}}{\sin^2 \frac{1}{2} \angle BAC} = \frac{28BD^2 \cdot AD}{\sin^3 \frac{1}{2} \angle BAC}.\]We can also write
\[[ABC] = \frac{1}{2} \cdot BC \cdot AD = \frac{1}{2} \cdot (BD + CD) \cdot AD = \frac{1}{2} \cdot 4r \cdot AD = 2r \cdot AD.\]Hence,
\[\frac{28BD^2 \cdot AD}{\sin^3 \frac{1}{2} \angle BAC} = 2r \cdot AD.\]Then $14BD^2 = \sin^3 \frac{1}{2} \angle BAC \cdot r = \sin^3 \frac{1}{2} \angle BAC \cdot \frac{BD}{2},$ so $\sin^3 \frac{1}{2} \angle BAC = 28BD.$

Since $\sin^3 \frac{1}{2} \angle BAC$ is between 0 and 1, $BD$ must be a fraction.  Since $BD$ is half the length of a side of triangle $ABC,$ it must be less than 1.  The only way this can happen is if $\angle BAC$ is obtuse.

